result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

The defendant Suzanne M Zettle was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of THC, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(e).
  • Possess Drug Paraphernalia, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.573(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Maintain full-time work, school or combination of the two.

To commit no further criminal acts during the period of the agreement.   Not to possess or consume any controlled substances without a valid prescription and then only take in the amount and frequency prescribed.  Not to possess or use any drug paraphernalia.

Cooperate with truthful testimony, as needed, in the cases of all co-actors. Cooperate with a full debriefing with investigators as to the drug activity of defendant and all co-actors. Debriefing to occur after pleas on this and themisdemeanor charges in this file, but before the sentencing hearing on the misdemeanor charges. Comply with any and all rules of probation and successfully complete any term of probation.   Defendant shall provide a copy of this agreement, along with the Criminal Complaint, to any counselor and sign any and all releases necessary to allow the counselor (or agency) to report compliance or lack thereof to the District Attorney's Office.  Any assessments done without this agreement and the Criminal Complaint(s) being supplied to the counselor will be considered violations of this agreement and not be accepted.  This agreement may be revoked or the defendant may have to complete a new assessment.

$250 fine plus costs on each count.   If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt. To pay supervision fees as ordered by the Dept. of Corrections.
Complete any counseling, evaluations, programs and assessments as appropriate resulting from the Department's COMPAS assessment.

timeConds.notes: 60 days stayed. To be used at the Court's discretion by petition from probation agent. Huber release granted. 60 days to report. Court has no objection to jail sentence being broken into 2  -  15 day periods.

Deferred Acceptance of Guilty Plea Agreement

Defendant Suzanne M Zettle in court with attorney Lawrence Gerard Vesely.  Raymond Pelrine appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Minute sheet. State amends Ct. 2 to Misd. Possession of THC,  gives plea agreement.  Court questions defendant on change of plea.  Rights/elements/max. penalties reviewed with defendant.  Defendant enters no contest plea to Ct. 1, amended Ct. 2 and Ct. 4.  Defense stipulates to factual basis to accept plea.  Court finds pleas made freely, knowingly and voluntarily, accepts pleas, and finds guilty of amended Ct. 2 and Ct. 4 as charged. Court withholds acceptance of the plea on Ct. 1 to allow defendant time to complete terms of the Deferred Acceptance of Guilty Plea Agreement. Court dismisses Ct. 3 but reads in for sentencing. Upon successful completion of DAGPA, State will, after 2 years, move to dismiss Ct. 1 and matter can be disposed by written stipulation.  Court reviews collateral consequences if defendant should be convicted of a felony, possible penalties. Court reviews DAGPA with defendant, approves and signs agreement. State/Defense make joint sentencing recommendation. Court makes statement, imposes sentence. Bond remains in effect regarding Ct. 1. DPAH hearing scheduled for 2/26/18 at 11:45 am.
